Problem Statement -Introduction to Neural networks - Renewood¶

Context¶

Renewable energy sources play an increasingly important role in the global energy mix, as the effort to reduce the environmental impact of energy production increases.

Out of all the renewable energy alternatives, wind energy is one of the most developed technologies worldwide. The U.S. Department of Energy has put together a guide to achieving operational efficiency using predictive maintenance practices.

Predictive maintenance uses sensor information and analysis methods to measure and predict degradation and future component capability. The idea behind predictive maintenance is that failure patterns are predictable and if component failure can be predicted accurately and the component is replaced before it fails, the costs of operation and maintenance will be much lower.

The sensors fitted across different machines involved in the process of energy generation collect data related to various environmental factors (temperature, humidity, wind speed, etc.) and additional features related to various parts of the wind turbine (gearbox, tower, blades, break, etc.).

Objective¶

ReneWind is a company working on improving the machinery/processes involved in the production of wind energy using machine learning and has collected data on generator failure of wind turbines using sensors. They have shared a ciphered version of the data, as the data collected through sensors is confidential (the type of data collected varies with companies). Data has 40 predictors, 20000 observations in the training set, and 5000 in the test set.

The objective is to build various classification models, tune them, and find the best one that will help identify failures so that the generators can be repaired before failing/breaking to reduce the overall maintenance cost. The nature of predictions made by the classification model will translate as follows:

True positives (TP) are failures correctly predicted by the model. These will result in repair costs.

False negatives (FN) are real failures where there is no detection by the model. These will result in replacement costs.

False positives (FP) are detections where there is no failure. These will result in inspection costs.

It is given that the cost of repairing a generator is much less than the cost of replacing it, and the cost of inspection is less than the cost of repair.

I in the target variable should be considered as failure and 0 represents No failure.

Data Dictionary¶

The data provided is a transformed version of the original data which was collected using sensors.

Train.csv To be used for training and tuning of models.

Test.csv To be used only for testing the performance of the final best model.

Both datasets consist of 40 predictor variables and 1 target variable.

def plot(history, name):
    """
    Function to plot loss/accuracy

    history: an object which stores the metrics and losses.
    name: can be one of Loss or Accuracy
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots() #Creating a subplot with figure and axes.
    plt.plot(history.history[name]) #Plotting the train accuracy or train loss
    plt.plot(history.history['val_'+name]) #Plotting the validation accuracy or validation loss

    plt.title('Model ' + name.capitalize()) #Defining the title of the plot.
    plt.ylabel(name.capitalize()) #Defining the label for the x-axis.
    plt.xlabel('Epoch') #Defining the label for the x-axis.
    fig.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc="outside right upper") #Defining the legend, loc controls the position of the legend.
In [29]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using statsmodels
def model_performance_classification(
    model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5
):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """

    # checking which probabilities are greater than threshold
    pred = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    # pred_temp = model.predict(predictors) > threshold
    # # rounding off the above values to get classes
    # pred = np.round(pred_temp)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1 Score": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  1. Predicting 'No Failure' when there is a 'Failure': This is a False Negative (FN). The model fails to detect an actual failure. As mentioned in the problem statement, this leads to a high replacement cost. Minimizing these is crucial.
  2. Predicting 'Failure' when there is 'No Failure': This is a False Positive (FP). The model incorrectly predicts a failure when there isn't one. This leads to an inspection cost.

Which case is more important?

Based on the problem statement:

  1. False Negatives (Predicting 'No Failure' when there is a 'Failure') result in high replacement costs.
  2. False Positives (Predicting 'Failure' when there is 'No Failure') result in lower inspection costs.

Since the cost of replacement is much higher than the cost of inspection, minimizing False Negatives is the more critical objective for this problem. This means we want our model to be good at identifying actual failures, even if it means predicting a failure occasionally when there isn't one (False Positive). How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives?

  • `Minimizing False Negatives is the most crucial goal. To minimize False Negatives, we need to maximize Recall for the 'Failure' class (Target = 1). While Recall is the main focus, we should also consider Precision (to keep False Positives and associated inspection costs in check) and the F1-score (which balances Recall and Precision) as secondary metrics to get a more complete picture of the model's performance.

In summary, the primary evaluation metric for this problem is Recall.

As we have are dealing with an imbalance in class distribution, we will be using class weights to allow the model to give proportionally more importance to the minority class.

# Calculate class weights for imbalanced dataset
cw = (y_train.shape[0]) / np.bincount(y_train)

# Create a dictionary mapping class indices to their respective class weights

  • However, the validation performance of Model 1 is slightly lower than Model 0 in terms of accuracy, recall, and F1 score.
  • The loss and accuracy plots show that while the training loss decreases and training accuracy increases, there is some fluctuation in the validation loss and accuracy, suggesting that the addition of momentum with the current learning rate might be causing the model to overshoot the optimal point on the validation set at times.
  • While Model 1's training metrics are impressive, the slightly reduced validation performance compared to Model 0 suggests that the added momentum might not be providing a consistent improvement in generalization on this specific network architecture and hyperparameters.

  • The use of class weights seems to have helped the model in achieving a good recall for the minority class (failure), which is the primary evaluation metric for this problem.
  • The loss plot shows that the training and validation loss decrease steadily over the epochs, indicating that the model is learning effectively. The validation loss is close to the training loss, further supporting the observation that the model is not overfitting.

Observations on Model 7 Performance on Test Data:

  • Overall High Performance: The model maintains high performance on the test data, with an overall accuracy of 0.9862 and a weighted average F1 score of 0.99.
  • Strong Majority Class Prediction: Similar to the training and validation sets, the model performs exceptionally well on the majority class (No Failure), with high precision, recall, and F1-score (all 0.99).
  • Good Minority Class Prediction: For the minority class (Failure), the model achieves a precision of 0.88 and a recall of 0.88. This means that when the model predicts a failure on the test set, it is correct 88% of the time, and it correctly identifies 88% of the actual failures.
  • Reasonable Balance: The F1-score for the minority class is 0.88, indicating a good balance between precision and recall for predicting failures on unseen data.
  • Consistency: The performance on the test data is consistent with the performance observed on the validation data, suggesting that the model generalizes well to unseen data. Conclusion:

The final model (Model 7) demonstrates strong performance on the test dataset, effectively handling the class imbalance and achieving a good balance between identifying actual failures (Recall) and minimizing false alarms (Precision). The high Recall for the minority class is particularly important for this problem's objective of minimizing costly generator replacements.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights & Recommendations:

  1. High Recall for Failure Prediction: The final model demonstrates a good ability to identify actual generator failures (Recall of 0.88 for the failure class on unseen test data). This is crucial for ReneWind as it helps minimize costly generator replacements by allowing for predictive maintenance.
  2. Manageable False Positives: While prioritizing Recall, the model also maintains a reasonable Precision of 0.88 for the failure class. This means that when the model predicts a failure, it is correct most of the time, which helps keep inspection costs due to false alarms in check.
  3. Utilize Model for Predictive Maintenance: Implement the developed neural network model within ReneWind's operational framework. The model's predictions can be used to schedule inspections and maintenance for generators identified as likely to fail.
  4. Set an Appropriate Probability Threshold: The current evaluation uses a default threshold of 0.5 for classifying predictions. Depending on the exact costs of inspection versus replacement, the probability threshold can be adjusted to further optimize the trade-off between False Positives and False Negatives. A lower threshold would increase Recall (identifying more failures) but potentially decrease Precision (more false alarms and inspection costs). A cost-benefit analysis based on the actual costs provided by ReneWind would be beneficial to determine the optimal threshold.
  5. Continuous Monitoring and Retraining: Sensor data can change over time due to various factors (e.g., environmental changes, aging of turbines). It is recommended to continuously monitor the model's performance on new data and retrain the model periodically with the latest data to ensure its predictions remain accurate and relevant.
  6. Investigate False Negatives: Although the Recall is high, there are still some False Negatives (actual failures not predicted by the model). Investigating these instances could provide valuable insights into failure patterns not captured by the current features or model, potentially leading to improvements in data collection or model architecture.
  7. Explore Feature Importance: While the features are ciphered, exploring techniques to understand which features contribute most to the model's predictions could be beneficial. This might involve using model interpretation techniques (if applicable to this type of model and data) or working with ReneWind to understand the potential real-world meaning behind the most influential ciphered features. This could lead to insights for improving sensor data collection or turbine design.
  8. Consider Advanced Techniques for Imbalanced Data: While class weights were used, further exploration of other techniques for handling class imbalance (e.g., oversampling the minority class, undersampling the majority class, using specialized algorithms) could potentially yield further improvements.

By implementing this model and following these recommendations, ReneWind can significantly enhance its predictive maintenance capabilities, leading to reduced operational and maintenance costs associated with wind turbine generator failures.
